Title : Glen Kelly
Text : {{for|the boxer|Glen Kelly (boxer)}}
'''Glen Kelly''' is a music arranger (especially of dance music) and composer.  He is best known for his musical theatre arrangements for [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] shows including ''[[Beauty and the Beast (musical)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', ''[[The Producers (musical)|The Producers]]'', ''[[Young Frankenstein (musical)|Young Frankenstein]]'', ''[[Spamalot]]'', ''[[The Drowsy Chaperone]]'', ''[[The Book of Mormon]]'' and ''[[Aladdin (2011 musical)|Aladdin]]''.

==Career==
Kelly is a self-taught musician, who began his career working as a rehearsal pianist and musical director the San Francisco show ''Beach Blanket Babylon''. He moved to New York in the early 1980s.<ref name=times>Weinert-Kendt, Rob. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/29/theater/the-arranger-glen-kelly-knows-the-broadway-score.html?_r=0 A Tailor of Music, Skilled in Alterations"] ''The New York Times'', June 26, 2014</ref> Kelly has had a long professional association with [[Mel Brooks]] and [[Susan Stroman]], notably on the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musicals ''[[The Producers (musical)|The Producers]]'' (2001–2007) and ''[[Young Frankenstein (musical)|Young Frankenstein]]'' (2007–2009).<ref name=times/>

His other arrangements for musicals and his [[incidental music]] for plays include ''[[Dance a Little Closer]]'' (1983), ''[[The Tap Dance Kid]]'' (1983–1985), ''[[Beauty and the Beast (musical)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' (1994–2007), ''[[Steel Pier (musical)|Steel Pier]]'' (1997), ''[[High Society (musical)|High Society]]'' (1998), ''[[The Frogs (musical)|The Frogs]]'' (2004), ''[[Spamalot]]'' (2005–2009), ''[[The Drowsy Chaperone]]'' (2006–2007), ''All About Me'' (2010), ''[[The Scottsboro Boys (musical)|The Scottsboro Boys]]'' (2010), ''[[The Book of Mormon]]'' (2011–present), ''[[Death of a Salesman]]'' (2012 revival), ''[[A Christmas Story: The Musical]]'' (2012), ''[[The Nance]]'' (2013; [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Music in a Play]]), ''[[Aladdin (2011 musical)|Aladdin]]'' (2014–present), ''[[Bullets Over Broadway (musical)|Bullets Over Broadway]]'' (2014), and ''Something Rotten!'' (2015).<ref>[http://rottenbroadway.com/cast.php "''Something Rotten!": The Rotten Players''], Something Rotten, accessed March 28, 2015</ref>

